  "prompt": "How are belly buttons formed?",
  "response": "Belly buttons, also known as navels, are formed as a natural part of the development process in the womb. Here\u2019s how it happens:\n\n1. **Umbilical Cord Connection**: During pregnancy, the umbilical cord connects the developing fetus to the placenta in the mother's uterus. This cord supplies oxygen and nutrients to the baby and removes waste products.\n\n2. **Post-Birth Separation**: After birth, the umbilical cord is no longer needed. It is clamped and cut, leaving a small stump attached to the baby's abdomen.\n\n3. **Healing Process**: Over the next 1 to 2 weeks, the umbilical stump dries out, hardens, and eventually falls off. This process is a natural part of healing.\n\n4. **Formation of the Belly Button**: The area where the umbilical cord was attached heals and forms a scar, which becomes the belly button. The shape and appearance of the navel (innie or outie) depend on factors like how the scar tissue forms, how the muscles heal, and genetic factors.\n\nIn summary, belly buttons are essentially scars left behind after the umbilical cord is detached and healed after birth.",
